UDFS¶

In [ ]:
# UDF to drop a column
def drop(df, columns, list_to_remove_from=None):
    columns = [columns] if type(columns) != list else columns
    if columns[0] in df.columns:
        df = df.drop(columns, axis=1)
    
    if list_to_remove_from is not None:
        if columns[0] in list_to_remove_from:
            [list_to_remove_from.remove(col) for col in columns]

        return df, list_to_remove_from
    
    return df

In [ ]:
import missingno as msno
# !!python3 -m pip install install missingno

msno.heatmap(df)
Out[ ]:
<AxesSubplot:>

There are some suggestions here that a missing value in sellerpostcode, owners, and vrm is related so that a "None" value here is actually encoding "No previous owner".

High correlations between missing registration year and mileage would also suggest that the car is not registered yet and we could set the registration year to the current year.

Missing VRM seems to directly map to missing mileage as well as registration year which would suggest "None" in mileage is actually 0 miles.

# Converting some string labels to integer:
import re

df["registration-year"] = df["registration-year"].apply(lambda x: x[:4] if type(x) == str else x)  # keep only first 4 integers (which is year)

def keep_only_integers(df, columns=[]):
    for c in columns:
        print("Converting", c, "to integer.")
        df[c] = df[c].apply(lambda x: int(re.sub("[^0-9.]", "", str(x))) if type(x) == str else x).astype("Int64")
    return df

def keep_only_float(df, columns=[]):
    for c in columns:
        print("Converting", c, "to float.")
        df[c] = df[c].apply(lambda x: float(re.sub("[^0-9.]", "", str(x))) if type(x) == str else x).astype(float)
    return df

df = keep_only_integers(df=df, columns=["seats", "doors", "manufactured-year", "registration-year"])
df = keep_only_float(df, columns=["engine-size", "price", "co2Emissions", "mileage"])

def replace_with_bool(df, col_val_pairs, new_col_names):
    for c in col_val_pairs.keys():
        df[new_col_names[c]] = df[c].map(lambda x: None if type(x) != str else x == col_val_pairs[c])
    return df

Instead of just imputing with the most frequent value, lets find the most frequent value dependent on car model and make for higher accuracy

In [ ]:
from collections import Counter
cols_to_impute_based_on_model_make = ["fuel-type", "body-type", "engine-size", "doors", "seats", "co2Emissions", "annual_tax", "years_since_manufacture", "is_automatic"]


def imputing_based_on_other_columns(df, varname, other_cols, fit=None):
    if fit is None:
        # Fitting to training data
        # Car models and makes which we sometimes lack manufacture year:
        cars_with_missing_varname = df[df[varname].isna()].groupby(other_cols).all()

        # All car models and makes and a list where varname values present
        all_other_cols_combinations = df[other_cols + [varname]].dropna().groupby(other_cols)[varname].apply(list)

        # The car models and makes we sometimes miss year from but its present in at least one other row
        intersection = set.intersection(set(list(all_other_cols_combinations.index)), set(list(cars_with_missing_varname.index)))

        # A dictionary with the most frequent manufacture year for the car models and makes defined above
        fit = all_other_cols_combinations[list(intersection)].apply(lambda x: Counter(list(x)).most_common(1)[0][0]).to_dict()

        example_othercols = list(fit.keys())[0]
        print("Example:", example_othercols, ":", fit[example_othercols])

    # Replacing missing manufacture year according to dictionary above if car make and model exists in dictionary
    print("number missing before:", sum(df[varname].isna()))
    df[varname][df[varname].isna()] = df.apply(
        lambda x: fit[tuple(x[var] for var in other_cols)] 
        if tuple(x[var] for var in other_cols) in fit.keys()
        else x[varname], axis=1)
    print("number missing after:", sum(df[varname].isna()))

    return df, fit

for varname in cols_to_impute_based_on_model_make:
    print("Imputing varname:", varname)
    training_df, fit = imputing_based_on_other_columns(training_df, varname = varname, other_cols=["model", "make"])
    test_df, fit = imputing_based_on_other_columns(test_df, varname=varname, other_cols=["model", "make"], fit=fit)

def fillna_mode(df, varnames, modes=None):
    if modes is None:
        modes = df[varnames].mode().transpose()
    df[varnames] = df[varnames].fillna(modes[0])
    return df, modes

training_df, modes = fillna_mode(training_df, varnames=cols_to_impute_based_on_model_make)
test_df, modes = fillna_mode(test_df, varnames=cols_to_impute_based_on_model_make, modes=modes)

The title column looks to be formatted in a set way, matching other column values. So lets only extract the words that are new (i.e. information not contained in other columns). This query takes a while, 10 minutes ish.

As doors seems to sometimes be encoded as "5dr" or "5d" in the title we make two columns to represent that. Same with automatic transmission which is listed as "auto" in title

def extract_new_words(df, varname, lookup_columns):

                            #    and (w not in x["make"].split(' '))) # because make can be two words e.g. alfa romeo 
                              ], axis=1)

Looks like theres some useful information here, such as s/s = start/stop. SE = special edition, 4WD = 4 wheeler, V6 is a specific type of engine etc.

Let's take a Bag-Of-Words approach, that is define a dictionary of frequent words and encode their presence/abscence as boolean columns in our dataset. This approach seems suitable as the ordering of words doesnt seem to matter too much in the title, and theres not much stop words or connecting words.

# from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer

def vectorize_words(df, varname, words):
    vectorised_columns = []
    for word in words:
        col_name = "title_contains_"+word
        df[col_name] = df[varname].apply(lambda x: any([word == w for w in x]))
        vectorised_columns.append(col_name)
    return df, vectorised_columns

training_df, vectorised_columns = vectorize_words(training_df, varname="adverttitle", words=top_words)

test_df["adverttitle_as_list"] = test_df["adverttitle"].str.split(' ')
test_df, vectorised_columns = vectorize_words(test_df, varname="adverttitle", words=top_words)

def plotting_numerical_vars(df, indvar, title='', depvar='', colorint=0):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,3,figsize=(16,4), constrained_layout=True)
    #set off Scientific notation from X-axis
    for i in range(0,3):
        ax[i].get_xaxis().get_major_formatter().set_useOffset(False)
        ax[i].get_xaxis().get_major_formatter().set_scientific(False)
    fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=16)
    sns.histplot(x=df[indvar], color=sns.color_palette("deep")[colorint],bins=50, ax=ax[0])
    ax[0].set_xlabel(indvar)
    ax[0].set_ylabel("Frequency")
    sns.boxplot(x=df[indvar],color=sns.color_palette("deep")[colorint], ax=ax[1])
    ax[1].set_xlabel(indvar)
    if depvar != '':
        sns.scatterplot(data=df, y=depvar, x=indvar, color=sns.color_palette("deep")[colorint], ax=ax[2])
        ax[2].set_xlabel(indvar)
        ax[2].set_ylabel(depvar)


for i in range(0,len(numerical_vars)):
    print("plotting :", numerical_vars[i])
    colorint = i-10 if i >= 10 else i  # to avoid running out of colours
    if numerical_vars[i] == y_var:
        plotting_numerical_vars(df=training_df, title=numerical_vars[i], indvar=numerical_vars[i], colorint=colorint)
    else:
        plotting_numerical_vars(df=training_df, title=numerical_vars[i], indvar=numerical_vars[i], depvar=y_var, colorint=colorint)

def plot_rare_line(df, varnames, min_freq_prop=0.05, colorint=0):
    print("Red line represents a minimum frequency level of {}%".format(min_freq_prop*100))
    min_freq = min_freq_prop*len(df.index)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(len(varnames),1,figsize=(7,20), constrained_layout=True)
    fig.suptitle("Rare Labels", fontsize=16)
    for i in range (0, len(varnames)): 
        var = varnames[i]
        sns.countplot(x=df[var], color=sns.color_palette("deep")[colorint], ax=ax[i])
        ax[i].axhline(min_freq, color="red")
        ax[i].set_xlabel(var)
        ax[i].set_ylabel("Frequency")
        ax[i].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=90)

def get_common_labels_dictionary(df, varnames, min_freq_prop=0.05):
    min_freq = min_freq_prop*len(df.index)
    common_labels = {}
    for var in varnames:
        label_frequency = df[var].astype(str).value_counts() > min_freq
        common_labels[var] = list(label_frequency[label_frequency].index)
    return common_labels

common_labels = get_common_labels_dictionary(training_df, nominal_data, min_freq_prop=0.01)

print(common_labels)
def set_rare_labels(df, varnames, common_labels):
    for varname in varnames:
        df[varname] = df[varname].astype(str)  # in case columns is not already string
        rare_labels = df[varname][~df[varname].isin(common_labels[varname])].unique()
        df[varname][df[varname].isin(rare_labels)] = "rare" if len(rare_labels) > 1 else  df[varname]
    return df

training_df = set_rare_labels(training_df, nominal_data, common_labels)
test_df = set_rare_labels(test_df, nominal_data, common_labels)

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn import tree
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error 
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

def fit_gs_cv_tree(X, y, max_depth, min_samples_split):
    model = tree.DecisionTreeRegressor(criterion="squared_error", random_state=rand_seed)
    model = GridSearchCV(model,
                         param_grid = {'max_depth': max_depth,
                                       'min_samples_split': min_samples_split},
                         cv=5,
                         scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',
                         verbose=2)
    model.fit(X, y)
    print("Best Params:", model.best_params_)
    print("Best RMSE value:", np.sqrt(-model.best_score_))
    print(model.cv_results_)
    
    return model

def fit_gs_cv_forest(X, y, n_estimators, max_depth, min_samples_split):
    model = RandomForestRegressor(criterion="squared_error", random_state=rand_seed)
    model = GridSearchCV(model,
                         param_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
                                       'max_depth': max_depth,
                                       'min_samples_split': min_samples_split},
                         cv=5,
                         scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',
                         verbose=2)
    model.fit(X, y)
    print("Best Params:", model.best_params_)
    print("Best RMSE value:", np.sqrt(-model.best_score_))
    
    return model


def plot_predictions(y_train, y_train_pred, y_test, y_test_pred, label, ymax=2e6):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(10,4), constrained_layout=True)
    sns.scatterplot(y_train, y_train_pred, ax=ax[0])
    fig.suptitle('Evaluation of predictions on train (left) and test(right) set ')
    ax[0].set_xlabel ('True ' + label)
    ax[0].set_ylabel('Predicted ' + label)
    ax[0].set_xlim(0e6, ymax)
    ax[0].set_ylim(0e6, ymax)
    sns.scatterplot(y_test, y_test_pred, ax=ax[1])
    ax[1].set_xlabel ('True ' + label)
    ax[1].set_ylabel('Predicted ' + label)
    ax[1].set_xlim(0e6, ymax)
    ax[1].set_ylim(0e6, ymax)

def plot_tree(model):
    # !python3 -m pip install pydotplus
    from IPython.display import Image
    import pydotplus
    dot_data = tree.export_graphviz(model, out_file=None,
                                    rounded=True,
                                    filled=True)
    graph = pydotplus.graph_from_dot_data(dot_data)
    Image(graph.create_png())
    

def get_feature_importance(model, columns):
    feature_scores = pd.Series(model.best_estimator_.feature_importances_, index=columns).sort_values(ascending=False)
    # Creating a seaborn bar plot
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30, 24))
    ax = sns.barplot(x=feature_scores, y=feature_scores.index)
    ax.set_title("Visualize feature scores of the features")
    # ax.set_yticklabels(feature_scores.index)
    ax.set_xlabel("Feature importance score")
    ax.set_ylabel("Features")
    plt.show()

    return feature_scores

The much lower RMSE in test compared to train is likely explained by much fewer supercars being present in the test dataset

Supercar vs non-supercar RMSE

In [ ]:
training_df_super = training_df[training_df["price"] > 0.25e6]
test_df_super = test_df[test_df["price"] > 0.25e6]

X_train_super, y_train_super = training_df_super[X_varnames], training_df_super[y_var]
X_test_super, y_test_super = test_df_super[X_varnames], test_df_super[y_var]

training_df_non_super = training_df[training_df["price"] < 0.25e6]
test_df_non_super = test_df[test_df["price"] < 0.25e6]

X_train_non_super, y_train_non_super = training_df_non_super[X_varnames], training_df_non_super[y_var]
X_test_non_super, y_test_non_super = test_df_non_super[X_varnames], test_df_non_super[y_var]

y_test_pred_super = baseline_model.predict(X_test_super)
y_test_pred_non_super = baseline_model.predict(X_test_non_super)

print("Supercar RMSE is:")
print(mean_squared_error(y_test_super, y_test_pred_super, squared=False))

print("Non-Supercar RMSE is:")
print(mean_squared_error(y_test_non_super, y_test_pred_non_super, squared=False))

One solution to this could be to train seperate models. But how many supercars are there?

In [ ]:
print("Number of cars above 0.25e6:", len(training_df_super.index) + len(test_df_super.index))

Number of cars above 0.25e6: 279
Prop of entire dataset 0.0012375798438608943

That really isnt many. Only about 0.12% of the entire dataset. So not worth a seperate model + the model wouldnt have enough data to train on anyways.

Conclusions¶

  • We were able to predict the price of a car being - on average - 30k off. But if we exclude supercar outliers from the test set (cars > 250k), we predict with a 10k error.
  • If we train a model on only the non-supercars, we achieve a much higher accuracy - about 5k off

Other ideas/lessons for another iteration:

  • stratification on train/test split to avoid massively differing train test results (test did much better due to less supercars)
  • do something more with the advert text
